{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/0034058093A/1958032101/0270.xml":{"full_text":"\u201cDon't Delay Longer,\u201d;\nAFL-CIO Committee\nUrges President 'U\nPresident a letter detailing- the AH<\nCIO views on the need for immediate\naction for a tax cut, improved fed\neral unemployment compensation\nstandards, increased defense expendi\ntures, a comprehensive public works\nprogram, and a number of other anti\nrecession measures.\nMeany, in a hard-hitting keynote\nspeech earlier had warned the dele\ngates not to be \u201cmisled\u201d by the polit\nical soothsayers and spellbinders from\neither side.\n\u201cThe Democrats know they can\nmake political capital out of talking\nabout the recession and doing little\nabout it.\n\u201cThe Republicans hope to protect\nthemselves by hiding the fact) that\nduring a Republican Athninistration,\nthe economy has become dangerously\nsick.\u201d\nAs the AFL-CIO News went to\npress a final session of the confer\nence was to hear reports on the con\ngressional visitations and a final\nspeech by AFL-CIO Vice Pres. David\nJ. McDonald.\n-In his letter to the President, Meany\nsaid that \u2018\u201cwithout rancor or partisan\nship the actions proposed to date\nare not enough to meet the needs of\nthe situation.\u201d\nOutlining the AFL-CIO\u2019s program,\nMeany concluded that the need for\naction was so acute that \"waiting for\nthe first monthly unemployment fig\nures would be, in our opinion, un\nnecessary and unwise.\u201d\nThe President had said previously\nthat he would wait for the March fig\nures before deciding on a tax cut and\nother moves to stem the recession.\nAFL-CIO Vice President Walter P.\nReuther, chairman of the Committee\non Economic Policy, chairing a panel\nsession of the conference involving\nthree senators and a congressman,\ndeclared the recession \"will not cor\nrect itself.\u201d\nHe urged a two-pronged tax cut\u2014\nan increase in the personal exemption\nand authority for the government to\nInstitute, if necessary, a 90-day mora\ntorium on collection of withholding\ntaxes. He reiterated also the necessity\nfor passage of legislation to set new\nfederal standards for Jobless benefits.\nThe AFL-dO conference opened a\nfew hours before the government an\nnounced that unemployment had\nreached a 16-year high with 5.2 mil\nlion idle and amid a series of moves\nin Congress for public works and\nother anti-recession proposals.\nShortly after Harrison banged the\nopening gavel, Meany placed the\nblame for inaction to date Jointly on\nthe Administration and Congress. The\nAdministration, he said, is to blame\nfor shirt-sightedness, \u201cfor its basic\nlack of confidence in the American\npeople\u201d and because it has done \u201ctoo\nlittle until it's almost too late.\u201d\nThe Congress, he added, did not\nneed to wait for Administration lead\nership, \u2018it could it should have\nmoved before this.\u201d\nThe AFL-dO President warned\nthe delegates to maintain a sense of\nurgency and not to be misled by opti\nmistic prophecies that when the un\nemployment figures are reported next\nmonth \"things are going to be a lot\nbetter.\"\n\u201cOur troubles will not have dimin\nished unless unemployment Is down by\nat least 200,000 by a month from to\nday,\u201d he declared.\nHe gave top priority in the anti\nrecession program to a tax cut that\nwould immediately pump new pur\nchasing power into the economy\u2014an\nIncrease In the personal exemption\nfrom 9800 to 9700, or higher If neces\nsary.\nSecond priority should be given the\nKennedy-McCarthy bill to establish\nnew, updated federal standards for\nunemployment compensation. Meany\nsaid not. a single state had heeded the\nPresident\u2019s request for action on im\nprovements to meet a standard of Job\nless benefits equal to at least one-half\nof lost wages.\nMeany assigned third place to an\nincrease in defense spending to streng\nthen America\u2019s defenses against Com\nmunist threats.\nFinally, he called tor a sweeping\npublic works program In housing,\nschool construction, road building,\nhospital and airport construction that\nwould meet the needs In these areas\nand add to the country\u2019s wealth.\nOutlining the unemployment situa\ntion a few minutes after Meany fin\nished his speech, Labor Secretary\nJames P. Mitchell assured the dele\ngates that the Eisenhower Adminis\ntration was deeply concerned over un\nemployment and would take prompt\nsteps to combat It\nMitchell promised that the Admin\nistration would call for substantial\ncuts in taxes \u201cif necessary.\"\nMitchell was followed by Director\nStanley H. Ruttenberg of the AFT#\nOIO Dept, of Research, who gave the\ndelegates a detailed fill-in on the eco\nnomic outlook, commenting that the\nentire nation is now a '\u2018distressed\nlabor area\u201d and tagging the recession\nas the most severe decline since 1937\n38.\nAndrew J. Btemlller, director of the\nAFL-CIO Dept, of Legislation, re\nviewed various legislative proposals\noffered in Congress and by the Ad\nministration and said the President\u2019s\nplan to extend Jobless benefits on a\ntemporary basis are \"grossly inade\nquate.\u201d\nThe delegates broke up into seven\nregional meetings following the open\ning morning speeches and planned\ntheir mass descent on the Capitol to\nstir up action on the unemployment\nprogram.\nThe regional meetings were attend\ned by congressmen from the respec\ntive regions including Tobert H. Mac\nDonald (D-Maas.), Frank J. Thomp\nson (D-N. J.), Charles A. Vanik\n(D-Ohio), Carl Elliott (D-Ala.), Eu\ngene J. McCarthy (D-Minn.), 'Richard\nBolling (D-Mo.) and Lee Metcalf\n(iD-Mont.).\nSocial Ills\n(OonttMMd from Page One)\nthe channels of Community Services,\nin the role of voluntary social agen\ncies, the national CSC chairman said\nthat the trade union movement is\ndedicated to the principle that \u201cthe\nAFL-CIO member is, first and fore\nmost, a citizen of his community.\u201d\nUnion members, Mr. Beirne said,\n\u201chave accepted the challenge of this\nresponsibility, and have Joined with\nother social-minded community\ngroups and individuals to provide the\nkinds of services which are so needed\nin our urban industrial communities\u2014\nadequate programs for the chronically\n111, the emotionally disturbed, the mal\nadjusted child, the retired worker,\nfamilies In need of counselling, boys\nand girls in need of adequate recrea\ntion.\u201d\nHie said that, while the trade union\nmovement recognizes the important\nresponsibilities of government in\nmeeting the broad needa of the Amer\nican people in the health and welfare\nfield, there is still an important job\nto be done by the voluntary social\nservice agencies.\n\u201cLike the hot dog and baseball,\u201d\nMr. Beime'continued, \u201cthe voluntary\nagencies are thoroughly American.\nThey exist almost nowhere in the\nworld hut in America. They have de\nveloped out of the American genius\nfor voluntarism.\n\u201cAmericans seem to have a peculiar\ndrive to get together in voluntary\ncommittees and organizations when\never they see a need to be met or an\nobjective to achieve.\u201d\nHe reminded hla listeners that the\nlabor union, itself, \u201cis a voluntary or\nganization which came Into being\nwhen a group of workers voluntarily\nJoined together to accomplish a de\nsired end\u2014recognition and bargaining\nfor wages, for boors and for condi\ntions of work.\u201d\nThe speaker at the opening ses\nsion of the conference\u2014which will\ndiscuss such topics as public welfare\nand private agencies; mental health\nand retarded children, and the retired\nworker\u2014said that the program of\nCommunity Services has five princi\nple functions. He described these as\nteaching trade union members to\nknow the social services which are\navailable; to use them when neces\nsary; to serve them in volunteer Rapa\ncities; to support them financially,\nand to improve them where Improve\nment will benefit the total community.\nMr. Beime paid tribute to the Ohio\nState Community Services Committee\nand to Its chairman, Bay Boas, and its\nsecretary. Irvin Ryan, not only for ar\nranging the conference \u201cbut more Im\nportantly for their year-around ef\nforts la developing responsible labor\nparticipation In the network of health\nand welfare agencies that exist for\nthe betterment of nil of the people\nof Ohio.\"\nUo Perils, national director of\nCommunity Service Activities for the\n13.5-million-member AFL-CIO, will\nparticipate in the workshops sched\nuled for the two-day conference and\nwas the principle speaker at the dos\ning session on Friday, March 14.\nAlso assisting in conference plan\nning, in an advisory capacity, is Berk\nley Wlattersan, a member of the na\ntional CSA staff who acts in a liaison\ncapacity with the Labor Participa\ntion Department of the United Com\nmunity Funds and Councils of Amer\nica. Inc., which has its headquarters\nin New York.\nLabor Course\nIn Counselling\nOpened Here\nDuring tb* tact imiIom. which\nended March 7, there was 1$ gradu\nates oat of an enrollment of 80.\nCertificate* were awarded at the\nThird Annual AFL-OO Community\nService* Committee Institato which\nwas held March 15 at the Sheraton.\nGenerally the AFL-CIO Commun\nity Services Committee runs two\naeries of courses per year, but there\nis a possibility that a third session\ncovering legal procedures such as\ngarnishees and evictions will be add\ned.\n\"Interest is running so high this\nyear that we are thinking of conduct\ning a third counselling session headed\nby local judges and attorneys,\u201d says\nFielder.\nThe 14th Union Counselling Course\nwill consist of two speakers at each\nclass session with ample time for\nquestions following the lecture.\nSpeakers will include Daniel A.\nHester, UF Executive Director; W. E.\nFielder, Secretary, AFL CIO Com\nmunity Service* Committee; S. K.\nThomas, Ohio State Employment\nService; Richard Hendrick, Ohio State\nkanployment Service; Mrs. Donald\nHeld, Executive Director, Summit\nComity Tuberculosis and Health As\nsociation; Dr. J. T. Villanl, Director,\nEdwin Shaw Sanitarium; William C.\nBlank, Executive Secretary, Cuya\nhoga Falls YMCA; Leslie Flaksman,\nExecutive Director, Akron Jewish\nCenter; and Raymond R. Brown, Ex\necutive Director, Akron Community\nService Center.\nStUl other speakers scheduled are\nRev. Kenneth Downing, Executive Di\nrector, Goodwill Industries; Mrs. Hope\nBair, Supervisor, Bureau of Vo\ncational Rehabilitation; Paula Hessel\nschwerdt, Executive Director, Kate\nWaller Barrett School; Mrs. Ruth\nKnlffln, Executive Dir., Florence Crit\ntenton Maternity Home; Mrs. Wlnnl\nfred E. Whims, Executive Secy., Sum\nmit Comity Society for Crippled Chil\ndren; Robert Silvanik, Administrator,\nRehabilitation Center of Summit\nCounty; Dr. Louis KacaHeff, Medical\nDirector, Child Guidance Center; and\nJames Barbuto, General Counsel,\nSummit County Legal Aid Society.\nThe course is open to the public,\nand a fee of $5.00 has been set. This\nincludes all literature distributed dur\ning the eight sessions as well as an\n\"award dinner\" at the conclusion of\nthe course.\nAnyone desiring to enroll may do eo\nby calling W. E. Fielder at UF Head\nquarters, PO 2-7601.\nPublications Post\nGoes to Miller\nAFLi-GIO President George Meany\nhas appointed Saul Miller, managing\neditor of the AFL-CIO News, as direc\ntor of the Dept, of Publications.\nHe succeeds Henry C. Fleisher, who\nresigned to open his own public rela\ntions firm.\nMiller has held his present post\nsince AFL-CIO merger. Previously he\nwas on the staff of the AFL News\nReporter.\nA veteran newspaperman, Miller\nwas earlier director of New News\npaper Service In Washington, a news\nservice created in 1651 by the Inti.\nTypographical Union to serve a string\nof daily papers operated by the union.\nSocial Agencies Hurt by\nLow Jobless Benefits,\nAkronites Informed\n(Cwtlimd from Fift One)\nIn such cases, the AFL-dO offi\ncial pointed out, the load falls on the\nvoluntary social welfare agencies\u2014\neven though their budgets are \u201cill\nequipped to provide this secondary as\nsistance for any length of time and for\nany appreciable number of needy\npeople.\u201d\nThe primary responsibility for\nmeeting basic needs for food, cloth\ning, shelter and medical care, he told\nthe trade unionists attending the La\nbor Institute, lies with government.\nTo prevent this crisis from depleting\nthe treasuries of the voluntary agen\ncies, and thus preventing them from\nproviding the normal services to the\ncommunity, the. voluntary agencies\n\u201cmust call on the government to\nliberalize and modernize both unem\nployment compensation and public as\nsistance,\" he said.\nThe social work agencies, said Mr.\nPerlis, must serve as \u201cthe rallying\npoint for all citizens\u201d in the fight to\nimprove these basic government bene\nfits, adding:\n\u201cThey must fight f6r higher com\npensation payments over a longer\nperiod; they most work toward relax\ning of public assistance laws and ad\nministrative rulings during the tem\nporary period of unemployment, and\nthey must be the leaders in bringing\nthe surplus foods program to their\ncommunity as a further measure to\nprotect the health of the, American\npeople during this unemployment\ncrisis.\u201d\nMr. Perlis, whose department han\ndles the relationships between the 13.5\nmillion-member AFL-CIO and the so\ncial work agencies, warned that \u201cthe\nalternative will be the bankrupting of\nthe voluntary agencies and the crip\npling of their total program of pro\nviding auxiliary health, welfare and\nrecreation services for the commun\nity.\u201d\nAfter leaving. Akron Mr. Perlis\nwent to Columbus where he charged\n\u201cundemocratic and discriminatory\npractices\u201d' were being practiced in\nthe social work field today.\nHis remarks highlighted a luncheon\nsession at the Seneca Hotel, which\nbrought to a close a three-day ses\nsion of 300 trade unionists from all\nover Ohio, who had assembled here to\nexplore new ways in which the labor\nmovement can be increasingly effec\ntive in the social work field.\nAs evidence of discrimination, Mr.\nPerlis cited the growing tread on- the\npart of United Funds and Community\nChests to \u201cforce the withdrawal from\nfederated fund-raising of the Urban\nLeague, which has occurred in city\nafter city, Just to appease bigoted\nminorities.\u201d The tendency to throw\nthe Urban League out of these com\nmunity-wide programs, the AFL-CIO\nofficial said, \u201ctotally ignores the long\nyears of harmonious relationships that\nexisted prior to the current flare-up\nof racial hatred.\u201d\nMr. Perlis said that Community\nChests and United Funds \u201cattempt to\ndefend their surrender to the bigots\nby claiming that they have a larger\nresponsibility to the community.\u201d\nThis, he said, \u201cis a case of saying the\nend justifies the means,\u201d adding:\n\"Actually, the responsibility for\nupholding the democratic principles\nat American life are far more import\nant than the mere dollars involved.\nIn the long run, it is better to suffer\na temporary financial loss, than to\nretreat from areas of tolerance and\ngood-will that have existed for more\nN\nMato Sara Your Child\nSoot Wall From BOTH EYES\nBinocular vision (using both ayes) is essential\nfor good judgment of the distance of on\ncoming cars. Have your child's eyes checked\nbefore the age of four to give both eyes the\nchance to develop normally.\np\nCO-OP OPTICAL\n2SI7 Manchester Road H4>22t6\nl\nthan fifteen years and which were\nachieved only through painful strug\ngle.\"\nThe director of Community Oorvice\nActivities for the lS.S-milUon-mem\nber labor federation also declared It\nwas \u201chigh time\u201d that social work\nagencies allowed their employee to\nJoin organizations of their own choos\ning for collective bargaining purposes.\n\"Trade unionism,\" he said, \u201cis an\nintegral part of American life. It is an\namazing contradiction that the social\nagencies look to organized labor, on\nthe one hand, for financial support\nand service in the furtherance of their\nprograms, and yet resist, on the other\nhand, legitimate efforts of their own\nemployes to unionize for self-better\nment.\u201d\nSumming up the First Annual Ohio\nCommunity Services Conference on\nlabor\u2019s responsibility in the social\nwork field, Mr. Perils declared:\n\"The union\u2019s future lies in service to\nthe Individual\u2014to the humblest of us.\nThat\u2019s how the trade union move\nment was bora; that\u2019s how the trade\nunion movement will continue to\ngrow.\n\u201cThere is no substitute for service\nto the individual. Passing resolutions,\nmaking speeches, signing petitions are\nImportant, but more important than\nall of them is service\u2014the day-to-day\nservice to the individual.\u2019\u2019\n-\u00bb_/\nJoblessness Is\nStill on Rise\nIn County\n(Continued from Page One)\nwork week for factory workers to 38.5\nhours, the lowest for any February\nsince World War H.\nAverage weekly earnings in manu\nfacturing continued to shrink also to\n880.85, a slight drop from the Janu\nary average and fl.SS below the\nFebruary 1957 average.\nOther highlights of the employ\nment-unemployment report:\nInsured unemployment persona\ncovered by unemployment compen\nsation was up 1.4 million from\nFebruary 1957 to a total of 2.1 mil\nlion.\nThe national rate of insured un\nemployment was 7j5 per cent com\npared with 4.4 per cent a year earlier.\nFactory employment dropped 300,\n000 from mid-January to mid-Febru\nary to 155.6 million.\nThe number of unemployed 15\nweeks or longer increased by 300,000\nto 1,150,000. This figure had remained\nwell under the million mark since\nthe spring of 1955.\nAbout 3 per cent of the employed\nwere working short shifts in Febru\nary.\nThe latest statistics on unemploy\nment and other economic indicators\ntouched off a demand for action by\nthe Administration and Congress from\nJames B. Carey, president of the Elec\ntrical, Radio and Machine Workers.\nHe wired President Eisenhower urg\ning him to call on industry for a\nmoratorium on further layoffs, secur\nity in employment and income by in\nstituting guaranteed annual wage\nplans, increased wages to catch up\nwith productivity gains and coopera\ntive studies on automation.\n-Meanwhile the Federal Reserve\nboard announced the third reduction\nin thev discount rate since the reces\nsion began, dropping it from 2.75 to\n2.25 per cent.\nIf\nYMCA Capital Fund Drive\nSet to Open Aptil 15th\nTop personnel for the 1868 YMOA\nCapital Fund Drive will include War\nren E. Oerter, chairman of the Ad*\nvanned Gift Section and five Divi\nsional Chairmen: Paul E. Weimer,\nCentral Akron, Dolphin R. Macken\nroth, Cuyahoga Falla, Philip H.\nToung, East, Dr. Harold L. Nichols,\nNorth and West, and Bill F. Denning,\nSouth. X\nMr. Carter, Chairman of the Board\nof Carter-Jonee Lumber Co. has set up\nten teams to solicit some 300 indi\nviduals and companies prior to the\ncommunity-wide effort opening in\nmid-April.\nThe YMCA is seeking f 1,247,400\nfor renovation of present facilities and\nexpansion. The campaign has the full\napproval of the United Fund organ\nisation and the dates were set by their\nExecutive Committee.\nAnnual Sunday\nSchool Week\nIs Endorsed\n\u201cAmerica's Sunday Schools provide\na unique and vital need in these crit\nical days in world history. It is here\nthat the youth of our land, our most\nprecious resource, are taught faith in\nGod and understanding of the dignity\nof man.\u201d\nThus begins a warm personal en\ndorsement on behalf of the forthcom\ning 14th annual National Sunday\nSchool Week observance and was\nwritten by George Mesny, President\nof the AFL-CIO, to T. M. Martin,\nNational Chairman for the all-faiths\nevent. Mr. Martin is President of the\nLion Oil Company, a division of the\nMonsanto Chemical Company.\nThe message continued: \u201cThese are\nthe 'bedrock upon which to build a\ndemocracy of men ajid women who are\ngood citizens and good neighbors;\nmen and women of moral character,\njudgment and courage.\n\u201cBecause of this important contri\nbution, I urge all members of the\nAFL-CIO to participate wholeheart\nedly in National Sunday School Week\nfrom April 14 to 20\u201d.\nNational Sunday School Week,\nyearly planned under the auspices of\nthe Laymen\u2019s National Committee,\n.Inc., whose headquarters are in New\nYork City, is an observance that is\nhighly endorsed .by leaders throughout\nthe country. Its primary objective is\nto encourage a weekly attendance\nat Sunday School, Church or Syna\ngogue and to stimulate a study and\nreading of the Bible. This year the\n.Committee will use as its official\ntheme: \"Our Sunday Schools\u2014First\ntine of Defense.\u201d\nCanadian Hatters\nWin Pay Hike\nTen-day strikes of 2,900 millinery\nworkers in Montreal and Toronto\nended with wage increases and agree\nment by management to the union\u2019s\ndemand that the forms on which hats\nare made bfe purchased from Canadian\nmanufacturers rather than from\nChechoslovakia.\nThe strikers, who are members of\nthe Hatters, Cap St Millinery Work\ners, won packages of 15 per cent in\nMontreal and 16 per cent In Toronto.\nNew wage rates range from 66 cents\nan hour for beginners to 32 for major\nADVIRTIStNO AND PUBLICATION\nSINATOB HID DANNIE PBISIDINT\nn\nSTANLEY\nWARNER\nSTRAND\nTIm Super-Sonic H\u00abU Creature Me Weapon\nCould, Destroy\nR O D A N The Ilyins Monster*!\nFilmed In\nHell in Korea\nH\n#>m Parking Eaary Night attar 6 PM. at 77JM I,\nSome 2,000 teen enf women will\nhelp on the community divisions, so-\nHcitteg on a prospect card he ids I.\nthere will be no in-plant solicitation\nas such.\nThe formal opening of the T cam\npaign will be Tuesday, April lffth, at a\ndinner meeting at the Central T. The\ncampaign will close May 5. _\u25a0\nMajor renovations are proposed for\nthe 20-year-old Central T. building.\nPublic areas will be modernised,\nmotors, wiring and plumbing replaced.\nA four story addition, 27x80, will ho\nadded on Bowery Street to provide ad\nditional room for the Central Boys\u2019\nBranch now coping with 2,400 mem- V\nbers in an area designed fra- 1,000\nboys. The T Athletic Club win also r\nget more space. -ft';;\nMajor temrovesnente will be made\nat Camp Y-Noeh, replacing the 16\noriginal cabins built in 1980, modern\nizing kitchen, dining ball and hospital\nfacilities. AUtttonal lands will prevent\nencroachment of a housing project.\nMortgages on the Bast, Firestone *:K\nPark and Falls T will be paid off. New\nfacilities Include a winterized lodge\nat Y-Noah, a physical education unit V\nat Maple Valley, club rooms and a\ncraf t shop at the Falla Y, which Is\nused jointly by the YMCA. and YWCA.\nThe YMCA drive also includes Ak\nron\u2019s share of the world-wide YMCA\nBuildings for Brotherhood and current\nexpenses for YMCA World Service\nduring 1958.\nMembership of boys under 18 in- J\ncreased 81% In 1957. The boys used\nthe YMCA to the hilt with 788,289 boy\nparticipants In activities sponsored\nduring the year, ia Increase of 34,809 _|\nover the previous year. YMCA pro\ngrams were carried on in 40S differ\nent locations in the Akron area.\nThe YMCA is dedicated to com\nbatting juvenile delinquency te a pre- I\nventative way by providing con\nstructive youth program which can be\nshared by all youth.\nRegistration />|i\n(Continued from Page One)\ncoming Primary Election, the Board\nof Election offices will be open from\n8:30 A. M. until 9 P. M. Monday, Tues\nday and Wednesday of next week.\nNo one will be able to register for\nthe Primary Election after 9 P. M.\non Wednesday, however.\nIf you are not a registered voter,\nbecome one before'the (leadline.\nCampfield Hickman,\nFuneral Horn*\nFUNERAL DIRECTORS\n24 Hour Ambulance Service\nOxygen Equipped\n586 M Arm.. W. SH 5-3161\nBARBERTON, OHIO\n5-30\nFrod Arbogast fir Co., Ine.\nMakers of\nJITTER BUG HAWAIIAN WlGGLER\nHULA POPPER\n313 West North Street BL 3-2177\nAKRON 4, OHIO\n6-6\n4\nEna! Akron Insurance Agency\nGENERAL INSURANCE\nE. A. Wagner, Manager\n915 8. Market Streef PO 2-7635\nAKRON, OHIO\n6-6\nDemand Thu Label on {V\nYour Printing\n\nS\nAkron Allied Printing\nTrades Council\nBOX 127 AKRON 9, OHIO\n4-11\n/it\nOriginal Barbecue Metic\nRIB STEAK AND CHICKEN DINNERS\n52 Sort Market Street BL 1-019T\nAKRON, OHIO\n5-30 t.t\nNenuon C. WkMey, M.T,\nArthritis Lumbago Nervousness\nConstipation Paralysis Insomnia, Etc.\nMASSAGE and CABINET BATHS\nMake An Appointment Today.\n1930- IIth Stteer SW 4-7971\nQUYAHOQA FALLS, OHIO\n6-13","height":"25764","width":"20096"}}
